    "## Ethics\n",
    "\n",
    "### Data Collection and Bias\n",
    "Our team has carefully evaluated the potential for collection bias within the Kaggle \"AI Impact on Jobs 2030\" dataset. Because the risk scores are based on future projections, they are subject to the subjective judgment of the researchers and experts who originally labeled the data. This creates a risk of bias, where high-level formal education (like a Master's or PhD) may be viewed as more irreplaceable simply because the experts themselves possess those credentials. We will mitigate this by comparing these projections against historical trends of automation to see if the protective nature of education remains consistent across different data models.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Proxy Discrimination and Social Impact\n",
    "A central ethical concern of this study is the risk of proxy discrimination. Formal education levels and years of professional experience are often highly correlated with socioeconomic status, race, and geographic access to resources. By investigating whether a PhD provides a \"statistically significant reduction\" in automation risk, we acknowledge that we are studying a variable that is not accessible to everyone. We must be careful not to frame our results in a way that suggests lower-educated workers are at fault for their automation risk, but rather highlight how systemic barriers to education may create a disadvantage in the future labor market.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Honest Representation and Limitations\n",
    "To ensure the honest representation of our findings, our analysis will include measures of variance and uncertainty rather than just average risk scores. AI development is notoriously non-linear, as seen with the sudden emergence of Large Language Models, and a \"2030 projection\" is a snapshot of current expectations that could change rapidly. We will communicate these limitations clearly to prevent our model from being used as a definitive tool for high-stakes career or policy decisions. Our goal is to provide a reproducible and auditable analysis that contributes to the discussion on workforce transition without overstating the predictive power of our results.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Data Retention and Auditability\n",
    "In accordance with the project's lifecycle, we have established a data retention plan where all processed datasets and intermediate analysis files will be deleted upon the final grading of the project. To maintain auditability, we will document our entire methodology, from data cleaning to the final statistical tests, within our Jupyter Notebook. This ensures that our process is transparent and that any biases introduced during the wrangling phase can be identified and corrected by others in the research community.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Biases / Privacy / Terms of Use\n",
    "**Are there any biases/privacy/terms of use issues with the data you proposed?**  \n",
    "The datasets we are using are publicly available and anonymized, so there are no direct privacy concerns. There is no personally identifiable information. We will follow all citation rules and terms of use for both the Kaggle and OECD data. The real issue to worry about is projection bias. The Kaggle dataset is based on expert-labeled automation risk scores, not real observed outcomes. That means those scores reflect assumptions about which jobs are replaceable.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Are there potential biases in your dataset(s), in terms of who it composes and how it was collected?**  \n",
    "Yes. Large labor datasets usually focus on formal occupations. Gig workers and people in unconventional paths are probably not fully represented. Education and experience are also highly correlated with socioeconomic status and access to opportunity. The differences between the datasets are probably indicative of systemic inequality instead of just pure skill differences.\n",
    "\n",
    "**How will you detect these specific biases before, during, and after analysis?**  \n",
    "Before running models, we will check how education levels, sectors, and industries are distributed to see if certain groups are overrepresented or underrepresented. We will compare this to external labor statistics. During analysis, we will run subgroup regressions and test alternative model specifications to see if results are driven by specific groups. After analysis, we will report uncertainty measures and run sensitivity checks. If conclusions change under different assumptions, we will state that clearly.\n",
    "\n",
    "**Are there any other issues related to your topic, data, and/or analyses that are potentially problematic?**  \n",
    "Yes. Automation probability is a projection, not a guarantee of job loss. There is a risk that people interpret our findings as definitive career advice. There is also a risk of reinforcing narratives that lower education equals higher replaceability, which oversimplifies structural labor market dynamics.\n",
    "\n",
    "**How will you handle the issues you identified?**  \n",
